04822nam a2200757Ia 9780674292895DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20232023mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742928957 a10.4159/97806742928952doi  a(DE-B1597)642361  a(OCoLC)1379311422  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aQH331 7aSCI0080002bisacsh04a570.11 aReiss, Michael J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe New Biology :bA Battle between Mechanism and Organicism /cMichael J. Reiss, Michael Ruse. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPrologue -- t1 · Mechanism Triumphant -- t2 · Organicism Strikes Back -- t3 · The New Biology -- t4 · Health -- t5 · Sex and Gender -- t6 · Race -- t7 · Mother Earth -- t8 · God and the New Biology -- t9 · Biology Education -- tEpilogue -- tReferences -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this accessible analysis, a philosopher and a science educator look at biological theory and society through a synthesis of mechanistic and organicist points of view to best understand the complexity of life and biological systems.The search for a unified framework for biology is as old as Plato’s musings on natural order, which suggested that the universe itself is alive. But in the twentieth century, under the influence of genetics and microbiology, such organicist positions were largely set aside in favor of mechanical reductionism, by which life is explained by the movement of its parts. But can organisms truly be understood in mechanical terms, or do we need to view life from the perspective of whole organisms to make sense of biological complexity?The New Biology argues for the validity of holistic treatments from the perspectives of philosophy, history, and biology and outlines the largely unrecognized undercurrent of organicism that has persisted. Mechanistic biology has been invaluable in understanding a range of biological issues, but Michael Reiss and Michael Ruse contend that reductionism alone cannot answer all our questions about life. Whether we are considering human health, ecology, or the relationship between sex and gender, we need to draw from both organicist and mechanistic frameworks.It’s not always a matter of combining organicist and mechanistic perspectives, Reiss and Ruse argue. There is scope for a range of ways of understanding the complexity of life and biological systems. Organicist and mechanistic approaches are not simply hypotheses to be confirmed or refuted, but rather operate as metaphors for describing a universe of sublime intricacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aBiologyxPhilosophy. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Biology.2bisacsh  acharles darwin.  achristianity.  aconsciousness.  adevelopment.  aeducation.  aenvironment.  aeo wilson.  aevolution.  afinal cause.  agaia hypothesis.  ajames lovelock.  amachine metaphor.  amedicine.  aobesity.  arace.  areligion.  aschizophrenia.  astephen jay gould.  avaccines.1 aRuse, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074970008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUIUC Life Sciences 2023 eBook packagez978311123611740uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067429289540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674292895423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674292895/original  a978-3-11-074970-0  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-123611-7